Communities\cf0 \ul \ulc0 \

\fs26 \ulnone \
BuzzZap is based around Communities. Every member belongs to a community. Within a community you can be one of two types of user: a standard member, or a community leader. The only difference of course is that a community leader has access to the community manager, whereas a normal user does not. \
\

\f1\b Starting a Community
\f0\b0 \
In order to start a community you must visit the BuzzZap home page, go to the \'93start a community\'94 link. \

\f1\b \
Joining a Community
\f0\b0 \
To join a community, you must visit the BuzzZap home page, go to the \'93join a community\'94 link. A form will appear, and you must supply your own account details, and most importantly the community passcode which you should be told by your community leader. If for some reason you are not able to join your community, contact your community leader and they can do it for you.\

\fs40 \ul \
\cf5 \ulnone My profile page\

\fs26 \cf0 \
Your profile is own personal page that can be seen by other people. Certain information such as your email will not be visible to other members unless you are friends with them.\

\f1\b \
Editing your information
\f0\b0 \
Editing your own personal information is extremely easy. If you click on any editable field it will become editable, and to save it, simply click anywhere else on the page (of course, you cannot edit your community, or reputation, etc).
\fs40 \ul \

\f1\b\fs26 \ulnone \
Friend Feature
\f0\b0 \
The friend feature works just like any other friend feature. To send a new friend request, visit that member\'92s profile, and on the top right you will see \'93send friend request\'94. They will then receive the notification to accept or decline. You can see your friends list on the bottom right of your profile.\

\f1\b Badge Feature
\f0\b0 \
As you start using BuzzZap more and more, you will start to get rewarded with all sorts of different badges which tells other users what you have \
