\cf5 \ulnone Global and private competition pages\
\cf0 \ul \

\f1\b\fs26 \ulnone Starting a competition
\f0\b0 \
\
You can only start a new competition if you are either the leader of a group, or a leader of a community. If a competition is private, it means groups within a community compete against each other. If a competition is global, it means different communities compete against each other. So, starting a private competition is initiated by a group leader, and starting a global competition is initiated by a community leader. To start a competition, visit the competition page and click "start new competition". Then, enter all the opponents you want to compete against (maximum of four groups/communities). Afterwards, select which category you want the debate question to be about, and finally how long the competition lasts. A debate question will then be randomly picked. Each desired opponent will then receive a notification asking if they want to accept the invitation to get involved with the competition. Once all opponents have responded to the invitation, the competition will begin. Each opponent will be randomly chosen to argue FOR or AGAINST the argument, regardless of their true belief. This will bring out members' true ability to debate!
\fs40 \ul \
\

\f1\b\fs26 \ulnone Being involved in a competition
\f0\b0 \
\
The principal of how competitions work on BuzzZap are the same, regardless of whether the competition is global or private. On a competition, each group/community will have their own box/section. This box is where that group/community posts their own arguments. Each community/group is assigned to a colour so that it is clear which posts were posted by which team. However, other candidates can post in their opponents' box in reply to the main arguments that their opponents post. This is what allows the debate to get more liberal and interesting. The winning team is determined by which gets the most points. Getting an up vote on any post/comment/main argument made by your team will earn your team a point. Anyone who is not involved in the competition can vote/judge comments and posts.
